1 Background

Forwarded from Brad c/o Gina

After condensing some of our notes from the retreat, I came up with five possible themes for suggested projects that fit inside an overarching theme.
See below.
I think we want to investigate
- the extent to which the VOC/VOP data support these capabilities,
- or whether it points us to different or additional topics.

Here are a couple research questions (feel free to reword these)

  1. To what extent do Veterans or other stakeholders (e.g., clinicians, caregivers, etc) recommend research and development, or education/outreach, in any of the following areas?
  • Employment
  • Education
  • Travel (air and ground)
  • Leisure
  • Living at home (i.e., not in an institutional setting, reducing caregiver need)
  1. What type of R&D or E&O activities are recommended in each of these areas?

pack<-function(x){
  for (i in x){
    if (!require(i,character.only = T)){
      install.packages(i,dependencies = T,repos="https://cran.rstudio.com")
      require(i,character.only = T)
    }
  }
}

pvalue <- function(x, ...) {                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            
    # Construct vectors of data y, and groups (strata) g
    y <- unlist(x)
    g <- factor(rep(1:length(x), times=sapply(x, length)))
    #if (is.numeric(y)) {
    #    # For numeric variables, perform a standard 2-sample t-test
    #    p <- t.test(y ~ g)$p.value
    #} else 
      {
        # For categorical variables, perform a chi-squared test of independence
        p <- fisher.test(table(y, g),simulate.p.value = T)$p.value
    }
    # Format the p-value, using an HTML entity for the less-than sign.
    # The initial empty string places the output on the line below the variable label.
    c("", sub("<", "&lt;", format.pval(p, digits=3, eps=0.001)))
}

diagcol<-c()
for (i in condns){
  diagcol[length(diagcol)+1]<-which(str_detect(varinames,i))}

colnames(datafile)[diagcol]<-condns

datafile$Diagnosis<-NA
datafile$Num_conditions<-NA
for (i in 1:nrow(datafile)){
  Dx<-c()
  for (j in diagcol){
    if (datafile[i,j]=="Checked"){Dx[length(Dx)+1]<-colnames(datafile)[j]}
  }
  datafile$Num_conditions[i]<-length(Dx)
  datafile$Diagnosis[i]<-paste0("",Dx,collapse = ", ")
}

datafile$Diagnosis[datafile$Diagnosis==""]<-"No checked condition"
datafile$Num_conditions<-as.character(datafile$Num_conditions)

         `Work school` = recode(`Work school`, "Critical" = 4, "Important" = 3, "Minor Importance"=2, "Not Important"=1),

  ungroup()

5 Results summary

  • Traveling freely and Meeting most personal mobility needs were ranked higher than Going to work/school or Living with less assistance
  • Most people want researchers to develop wheelcahirs that self-adjust and portable power devices that a person with a disablity can use independently.
  • Smart wheelchair was the most desirable over Human-machine interfaces, wearable or modile tech, and alternate power sources
  • Devices that ease transfers and smart home tech to control lights, doors e.t.c. were more important to them than personal robots, brain implant, and virtual reality for training.
  • Also they consider Developing alternate wheelchair power sources more important than developing exoskeleton, foldable manual chair and self-driving wheelchair in that order.

Hierachical clusters:

Mobility needs ~ Travel needs > Less assist ~ Go to school/work

6 Identified issues and suggestions

-Framing of questions: ranking…
-Many disabling condns vary widely in QOL impact, effort should be made to qualify how they impact the volunteers
-Impact may determine the volunteer’s responses/ choice of what is important
-I think it’s more important to focus on what they find most challenging than their recommended tech solutions which will probably be biased based on what they think is possible or easy to achieve.
-Some of the questions overlap
